 <article class="markdown-article"> 







<div class=WordSection1>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;line-height:normal'><b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:24.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Pelvic inflammatory disease</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>What
is pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>PID&nbsp;</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>is an inflammatory disease of the fallopian tubes and uterine
appendages, most often resulting from infections.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The
disease is also known as</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Salpingo-oophoritis;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>salpingitis;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>oophoritis.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In English, diseases
are called Pelvic inflammatory disease.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Causes</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>PID causes infections
that ascend from the vagina and cervix to the uterine cavity and fallopian
tubes.&nbsp;Frequent pathogens include gonococcus, chlamydia, mycoplasma.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Infections are usually
sexually transmitted.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>PID is usually also
caused by other bacteria, including pathogens associated with bacterial
vaginosis (streptococcus and staphylococcus, etc.).&nbsp;Virus-causative agents
of PID include herpes simplex virus type 2 (HSV2), cytomegalovirus.&nbsp;In
15-20% of cases, the pathogen cannot be identified.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Who is
at risk</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Sexually active women;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>women with altered hormonal levels (pregnant women taking oral
contraceptives during menopause);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>women who underwent gynecological operations associated with
trauma to the mucous membrane (biopsy, curettage, hysteroscopy, etc.);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>women who have had a complicated pregnancy or childbirth;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Women who have had previous episodes of PID,&nbsp;<b>vaginitis&nbsp;</b>(inflammation
of the vagina), or&nbsp;<b>cervicitis&nbsp;</b>(inflammation of the
cervix).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>How
often does it occur</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>PID make up 50-60% of
all gynecological pathologies.&nbsp;The peak incidence occurs between the ages
of 17 and 28, it is associated with sexual activity and the lack of barrier
methods of contraception.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Symptoms</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Severe pain in the lower abdomen;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>temperature rise above 38 ° Ñ;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>violation, discomfort when urinating;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>bloating;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>mucous, pus-like, bloody discharge from the genital tract;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>discomfort during intercourse.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Diagnosis of the disease</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Questioning and inspection</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Inflammation is
detected on examination by a gynecologist.&nbsp;Details are specified using
laboratory and instrumental examinations.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Laboratory examination</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Clinical&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>and&nbsp;<b>biochemical&nbsp;</b>blood
tests will show general signs of inflammation: an increased level of&nbsp;<b>leukocytes&nbsp;</b>,
ESR,&nbsp;<b>C-reactive protein&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>dysproteinemia&nbsp;</b>(violation
of the ratio of protein fractions).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Microscopic method&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>-
examination of a smear will show immature epithelial cells,
leukocytes.&nbsp;When staining a smear for flora, the causative agent of PID
can be identified.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>A pap test (Pap smear)&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>is a
cytological&nbsp;<b>test&nbsp;</b>that detects precancerous or cancerous
cells.&nbsp;The test is necessary for all women who are sexually active,
especially those with a clinical picture of vaginitis.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>A pregnancy test is&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>done
to rule out an ectopic pregnancy that can produce similar symptoms.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>The polymerase chain reaction (PCR) method&nbsp;</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>accurately identifies the pathogen by determining its DNA.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Functional,
radiation and instrumental diagnostics</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The following methods
can help clarify the diagnosis and possible complications by determining the
signs of inflammation of the fallopian tubes, the presence of fluid in them,
the condition of the surrounding tissues:</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Ultrasound&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>of the pelvic organs;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>computed and magnetic resonance imaging (&nbsp;<b>CT and MRI&nbsp;</b>);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Doppler&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>study of the pelvic organs -
increased blood supply to the fallopian tubes;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>diagnostic&nbsp;<b>laparoscopy&nbsp;</b>- this endoscopic research
method, if necessary, can be transformed into a therapeutic one.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Treatment</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Treatment goals</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Improvement of the general condition;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>elimination of the pathogen from the uterus and vagina.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Lifestyle and aids</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Abstinence&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>from sexual activity during
treatment;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>upon detection of a sexually transmitted infection,&nbsp;<b>examination
of the partner&nbsp;</b>for the presence of the corresponding
pathogen.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Medications</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In most cases,
treatment is necessary for both the patient and her partner.&nbsp;Outpatient
treatment is usually sufficient, but if PID is severe and complications
develop, hospitalization is necessary.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Antibacterial drugs are prescribed after determining the
antibacterial sensitivity of the microorganism.&nbsp;Antibiotics are used from
the groups of&nbsp;<b>macrolides&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>cephalosporins&nbsp;</b>of
the 2nd and 3rd generations,&nbsp;<b>aminoglycosides&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>tetracyclines&nbsp;</b>in
oral, intramuscular and intravenous forms, depending on the severity of the
condition.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Other antibiotics - in some cases, antibiotics from the&nbsp;<b>lincosamide&nbsp;</b>group&nbsp;,&nbsp;<b>metronidazole,
are used&nbsp;</b>.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Surgical
operations</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>They can be prescribed
if drug treatment is ineffective, symptoms of intoxication increase, and
laboratory test data deteriorate.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Various operations are
performed:</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>tubectomy&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>- removal of the fallopian
tube;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>adnexectomy&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>- removal of the
appendages;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>salpingoovarolysis&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>-
dissection of adhesions between the fallopian tube and the ovary;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>salpingoneostomy&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>-
creating a hole in the fallopian tube;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>separation of&nbsp;<b>adhesions&nbsp;</b>(adhesions -
proliferation of connective tissue within and between organs) in the abdominal
cavity.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Possible complications</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Chronic pelvic pain&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>occurs
in 25% of patients with PID.&nbsp;Pain is usually associated with the menstrual
cycle or is a consequence of the adhesions.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Infertility&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>- Adhesions in the
fallopian tubes can interfere with the passage of the egg or sperm.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>A tubo-ovarian abscess is&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>found
in every third of those&nbsp;<b>hospitalized&nbsp;</b>for PID.&nbsp;An abscess
is a cavity filled with pus.&nbsp;The walls of the abscess can be the fallopian
tubes, the organs of the small pelvis, the intestines, and other organs of the
abdominal cavity welded together.&nbsp;When an abscess ruptures, inflammation
of the peritoneum develops -&nbsp;<b>peritonitis&nbsp;</b>, requiring urgent
surgical care.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Ectopic pregnancies&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>account
for 2% of all pregnancies.&nbsp;The transferred PID triples the risk of its
formation.&nbsp;A dangerous condition that threatens life and often leads to
infertility.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Infection of the baby during childbirth&nbsp;</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>- when passing through the natural birth canal, the baby can be
infected with genital bacterial and viral infections (gonorrhea, chlamydia,
herpes viruses and others).&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Prophylaxis</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Use of barrier methods of contraception (male and female condoms);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>going to a doctor for a laboratory check at the risk of infection;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>examination of a partner for infections when diagnosing PID in a
woman;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>avoiding vaginal douching, as this violates the natural protective
microflora in it.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Forecast</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The prognosis is
generally good: most infections are cured.&nbsp;However, chronic untreated PID
can lead to adhesions and scarring, female infertility, or ectopic
pregnancy.&nbsp;During vaginal delivery, infections can be transmitted to the
baby.&nbsp;It is important to identify the pathogen in a timely manner, since
almost all PID infections are completely curable.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>What
questions should you ask your doctor</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>What research do I need?</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Should the partner be examined and treated?</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>What if symptoms recur after treatment?</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Can I prevent recurring episodes of PID?</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Can you get pregnant after PID?</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Can I be treated at home or do I need hospitalization?</span></p>

